        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Rise of a genius</h2> 
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          <strong>The technology behind the microwave was originally developed to detect enemy planes during WWII, not to heat food</strong>. However, the microwave's journey began with an unexpected moment. Percy Spencer, a self-taught genius and the father of the microwave, was no stranger to ingenuity. Born in 1894 in Howland, Maine, Spencer left school at 12 to work in a weaving mill and joined the U.S. Navy at 18. By night, he taught himself calculus and physics.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-jan-4-1.jpg" alt="Rise of a genius" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          After World War I, Spencer joined American Appliance Company, co-founded by engineer Vannevar Bush, best known for organizing the Manhattan Project. In 1925, the company changed its name to Raytheon Manufacturing Company. His popularity rose as he became the go-to problem solver in the organization, and he also helped develop detonators. While Raytheon gained fame for military innovations, Spencer’s knack for inventive solutions would make history. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

