          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Happy accident</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Between 1937 and 1940, British physicist <a href="https://www.kcl.ac.uk/people/john-turton-randall" target="_blank">Sir John Turton Randall</a> and a team of British coworkers developed a multi-cavity magnetron that produced electromagnetic waves of a small wavelength (microwaves). The magnetron was given to the U.S. government in 1940 in exchange for their financial and industrial help during the Second World War. Raytheon was one of the companies that acquired the contract to build the magnetrons, and Percy Spencer was tasked to work on it as he was an expert in radar tube design.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In 1945, while working on a powered radar set, <strong>Spencer made a shocking discovery: The peanut cluster bar that he had in his pocket had melted</strong>. He wasn’t the first to notice this phenomenon, but he was the first to experiment further. He attached a high-density electromagnetic field generator to an enclosed metal box and experimented in a controlled environment. And just like that, the idea of using microwaves for cooking was born.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Innovation repurposed</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">After World War II, as wartime technologies transitioned to civilian use, the microwave oven began evolving into a household appliance. <strong>The concept of cooking with radio waves wasn’t new</strong>, as Westinghouse had demonstrated it at the <a href="https://antiqueradio.org/ShortWaveCraftNovember1933.htm?" target="_blank">1933 World’s Fair</a>. Percy Spencer’s innovation and strategic patent filings laid the groundwork for practical application.</p>
          </mj-text> 

          <mj-image padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-jan-4-2.jpg" alt="Innovation repurposed" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In 1947, Raytheon introduced the <strong>first commercial microwave, the Radarange</strong>. It was designed for industrial and commercial use, stood over 5 feet tall, weighed 750 pounds, and came with a hefty $5,000 price tag. It also required water cooling, limiting its accessibility. By 1955, Raytheon began licensing its technology, and <strong>Tappan released the first consumer-friendly model</strong>. However, with a price tag of $1,295 (around $11,000 today), it remained out of reach for most families.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The breakthrough came in 1967 when Raytheon’s subsidiary, <strong>Amana, introduced the countertop Radarange for $495</strong>. It was still a luxury, but it finally made microwave ovens affordable for many households.</p>
          </mj-text>

